# Smart Exercise Timer - Circuit Wiring Guide (Direct RPi Version)

**Note**: Since simulators like Tinkercad do not have a "GrovePi Shield" component, you must wire components **directly** to the Raspberry Pi GPIO pins.
This guide provides a pin mapping that works for the visual diagram.

## 1. Component List (Simulator Equivalents)
-   **Raspberry Pi 3/4**
-   **Breadboard**
-   **LEDs (x4)**: Standard LEDs + 220Ω Resistors.
-   **Push Buttons (x4)**: Tactile Switches + 10kΩ Resistors (Pull-down).
-   **PIR Sensor**: Standard PIR module (3 pins).
-   **Piezo Buzzer**: Standard passive/active buzzer.
-   **Temperature Sensor**: TMP36 (analog) or DHT11/22 (digital) depending on what's available.
-   **LCD 16x2 (I2C)**: Use the "LCD 16x2 (I2C)" component.

## 2. Direct Wiring Map (No GrovePi)

We will map the "Grove Ports" used in the code to specific "RPi GPIO Pins" for the diagram.

| Component | Grove Port (Code) | **Connect to RPi Pin** | Wiring Details |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **LED 1** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 5** (Pin 29) | Anode(+) -> GPIO 5 |
| **LED 2** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 6** (Pin 31) | Anode(+) -> GPIO 6 |
| **LED 3** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 13** (Pin 33) | Anode(+) -> GPIO 13 |
| **LED 4** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 19** (Pin 35) | Anode(+) -> GPIO 19 |
| **All LEDs** | - | **GND** | Cathode(-) -> 220Ω -> GND |
| | | | |
| **Button 1** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 22** (Pin 15) | Leg A -> GPIO 22 |
| **Button 2** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 23** (Pin 16) | Leg A -> GPIO 23 |
| **Button 3** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 24** (Pin 18) | Leg A -> GPIO 24 |
| **Button 4** | Direct GPIO | **GPIO 25** (Pin 22) | Leg A -> GPIO 25 |
| **All Btns** | - | **3.3V** | Leg B -> 3.3V |
| **All Btns** | - | **GND** | Leg A -> 10kΩ -> GND (Pull-down) |
| | | | |
| **PIR Sensor** | D8 | **GPIO 8** (Pin 24) | Signal -> GPIO 8 |
| **DHT Sensor**| D7 | **GPIO 7** (Pin 26) | Signal -> GPIO 7 |
| **Buzzer** | D3 | **GPIO 12** (Pin 32)* | (+) -> GPIO 12 |
| **LCD (I2C)** | I2C | **GPIO 2** (SDA) | SDA -> SDA (Pin 3) |
| **LCD (I2C)** | I2C | **GPIO 3** (SCL) | SCL -> SCL (Pin 5) |

> ***Note on Buzzer**: In the GrovePi code, D3 is used. However, on a real RPi, GPIO 3 is SCL (used by LCD). For the diagram, connect the Buzzer to **GPIO 12** (a PWM pin) to avoid visual conflict with the LCD wires.*

## 3. Breadboard Layout Strategy

### Step 1: Power
-   RPi **5V** (Pin 2 or 4) -> Breadboard **Red (+) Rail**.
-   RPi **GND** (Pin 6 or 9) -> Breadboard **Blue (-) Rail**.
-   RPi **3.3V** (Pin 1 or 17) -> Breadboard **Other Side (+) Rail** (for Buttons).

### Step 2: LEDs (The "Light Bar")
-   Place 4 LEDs in a line.
-   Connect all short legs (-) to the Blue Rail via 220Ω resistors.
-   Connect long legs (+) to GPIO 5, 6, 13, 19.

### Step 3: Buttons (The "Control Panel")
-   Place 4 Buttons below the LEDs.
-   Connect one side to 3.3V.
-   Connect the other side to GPIO 22, 23, 24, 25.
-   Add 10kΩ resistors from the GPIO side to GND (Blue Rail) to keep them stable (Pull-down).

### Step 4: Sensors & Output
-   **PIR**: Place on the left side. VCC->5V, GND->GND, Sig->GPIO 8.
-   **DHT**: Place on the right side. VCC->3.3V, GND->GND, Sig->GPIO 7.
-   **Buzzer**: Place near the LCD. (+) -> GPIO 12, (-) -> GND.
-   **LCD**: Place top-center. VCC->5V, GND->GND, SDA->GPIO 2, SCL->GPIO 3.

This layout will look professional and logically organized for your presentation!
